      "transcript": "Welcome, everyone. Let's jump right in. Director Hwang. In Season 2, since everyone already knows what happened in Season 1, I wanted to bring that same energy into the game again—but take it further, beyond just what feels familiar. We tried to show something new within the same space. So while we kept the elements fans loved—like the dormitory setting, for example—in Season 1, the old man, Oh Il-nam, secretly joined as a player, hiding his true identity—and it was only revealed at the very end as a twist. But in Season 2, I flipped that idea. This time, the audience already knows the Front Man is in the game. But Gi-hun and the players inside do not. So once again, Player 1 is actually the host—but in a way that creates a totally different kind of tension. We really tried to draw out new thrills and excitement that way.",
      "summary": "The video opens with the SAG-AFTRA Foundation presenting a conversation with the cast and crew of Squid Game. Director Hwang Dong-hyuk explains his approach to Season 2, aiming to maintain the energy of the first season while introducing new narrative twists, particularly regarding the Front Man's identity being known to the audience but not the players."
    },
    {
      "start_time": 151.0,
      "end_time": 598.0,
      "transcript": "Over the past three years, I wanted to really show how much effort Gi-hun put into finding the people behind the game. That was something I tried very hard to express. Both through his outward appearance and the energy that comes from his emotional state. I felt his character needed a significant transformation from Season 1. He had to be very different, inside and out. That was my belief and it was something Director Hwang emphasized in the script as well. So rather than the bright, lighthearted Gi-hun from Season 1, we needed to show a very different side of him, almost to the point where he feels like a completely different person. But if that's all we showed of Gi-hun, if he was serious all the time, it could become frustrating or even dull. So Director Hwang suggested that when he meets Jeong-dae, we let some of that old Gi-hun energy come through. Even if just briefly, he wanted the audience to catch a glimpse of the Gi-hun they once knew. And throughout filming, Jeong-dae really helped me bring that side of him back to the surface. He supported me with his acting and created the right atmosphere. So in Season 2, I tried to show both the changed version of Gi-hun and the version fans remember and love from Season 1. In Season 2, the Front Man finally takes off his mask and he performs as a new persona, Young-il, directly in front of the participants. So it became a series where I could show many different sides of the character. That made me excited and curious as an actor. There were a lot of fun and interesting moments while performing, but of course, it also came with challenges. This is a man who has completely lost hope in humanity, someone who has no faith left in the world. He's emotionally shut down, almost as if all feelings have been erased. So when someone like that tries to act like a normal person, can he really show things like excitement, joy, tension, or fear and make it feel real? That was the big question: could we convince the audience? Director Hwang and I had many conversations about that. And interestingly, when we experimented with different takes, when I allowed myself to express more, to push those emotions further—it actually felt scarier, more eerie, and unsettling. And that somehow fit the tone of Squid Game really well. So we decided to go all in—to express more and really play with the role. We made that choice consciously because it fit the unique atmosphere of this drama, and I believe it helped bring the character to life. Over the years, I've played a lot of different roles, but I've played a mother quite a few times. And in real life, I'm also a mom to one son. He's 33 now, and a wonderful young man. So my reality really aligned with the role I had to play. Just like any mom, I want my son to grow up well to become a good person. That's the heart I brought to this role, and I think that helped me connect with it deeply. And it helped that this was Yang Dong-geun's story; he played Yong-sik, my son in the show. That made it easier for me to immerse myself even more. And the role of a mother is something universal; just hearing the word 'mom' can bring people to tears. There's an emotional key in that, I think. And that became one of my biggest strengths in the game. As a cisgender actor, I did have concerns, real worries about playing a transgender character. And maybe because of that, I didn't want the portrayal to feel exaggerated or superficial. Since Hyun-ju is a transgender woman, I met with real transgender people. I asked questions, listened to their stories. I did a lot of research to try to build the character with honesty and care. I tried to avoid using exaggerated gestures or stereotypical voices. I didn't want to reduce her to a performance. Yes, Hyun-ju is transgender. But to me, that's just one part of who she is. What really mattered was her heart and her strength. So I focused on her inner life, her courage, her convictions. She's one of the few characters in the game who is truly selfless, deeply compassionate, with a quiet charisma and real leadership. That's the Hyun-ju I wanted to bring to life: strong, and beautiful in her own right.",
      "summary": "Lee Jung-jae discusses portraying Gi-hun's trauma and transformation, aiming to balance his new serious demeanor with glimpses of his old self. Lee Byung-hun explains the challenge of playing the Front Man's new persona, Young-il, and how pushing emotions made the character more unsettling. Kang Ae-sim shares how her real-life experience as a mother helped her connect with her character, while Park Sung-hoon details his research and approach to authentically portraying the transgender character Hyun-ju."
    },
    {
      "start_time": 598.0,
      "end_time": 1547.0,
      "transcript": "When preparing for the role of Thanos, I had countless deep conversations with Director Hwang. We went over everything, even the smallest details, together. Thanos isn't some cool, flashy rapper. He's a young man whose life went off track, now relying on drugs to cope. So I spent time researching the drugs he uses—what they do, how they affect the body and mind. The anxiety that hits when he can't get them, and the strange highs when he does. I really studied those emotional shifts and extremes. To be honest, the role made me confront parts of my past I wasn't proud of. There were things I had to face head-on, old mistakes I had buried. So it took real courage to step into this character. But the director trusted me fully, and that gave me the strength to go all in. Through Thanos, I wasn't just building a character; I was reckoning with who I had been. In a way, it felt like a personal reckoning, a kind of reflection and growth. And now it feels like a new chapter has opened for me. Not just as an actor, but in my life as well. I've learned so much from this journey. Thank you. Season 1 mostly focused on the dangers of unchecked capitalism, especially its endless competition. In Season 2, I wanted to go further, to explore new themes beyond that. One idea I wanted to focus on was voting. In Season 1, the vote happened only once. But this time, I wanted to make it a central part of the story. That decision also reflects the Front Man's confidence—his belief that no one is being forced to play; they choose to. The games exist only because the players themselves keep choosing them. As a creator, I also wanted to reflect on real-world elections, especially in so-called liberal democracies. We're told elections are the foundation of democracy. But more and more, they seem to divide us. They intensify anger and hostility instead of bringing people together. The flower of democracy is starting to wilt. Elections now reveal how divided we really are. That's what I see happening—not just in Korea, but in the U.S. as well. And although democracy is built on the idea of 'one person, one vote,' I wonder if that's still effective in today's world, when so many people get their information through biased algorithms. With misinformation and fake news everywhere, driven by AI and social media, it's easy to be manipulated. We live in a very propagandistic time. So the real question I wanted to ask is: can majority rule still protect true democracy? That's the dilemma I wanted to explore through the voting mechanic in the show. Many people wonder why is the Front Man so obsessed with Gi-hun? That's something I've thought about a lot too. My interpretation is this. Gi-hun wins the game and walks away. But then, he decides to come back to destroy the system from the inside. That choice... the Front Man sees it. And maybe, in that moment, he sees a reflection of himself. A version of who he once was, or could've been. So in some way, maybe there's a kind of attachment. But when he sees Gi-hun trying to take it all down, he thinks: 'Let's see what happens.' 'If you go through this again, will you still believe in people? Will you still have hope?' 'Let's see if you still fight for justice to the very end.' Because the Front Man believes Gi-hun will end up like him, disillusioned, broken, changed. So he keeps watching, trying to break his spirit. But at the same time, there's conflict inside him. His face is hidden, so his emotions are, too. But I believe even behind that mask, there are moments of doubt, hesitation, even regret. Maybe, deep down, he's rooting for Gi-hun to do what he himself couldn't do. Maybe he hopes Gi-hun will succeed. Even just a little. And at the same time, there's envy, too. He sees Gi-hun staying true to his beliefs, something he could never do. That mixture of hope, jealousy, confusion—it was all very difficult to express. But also incredibly rewarding as an actor. While filming the scene with the coup, what surprised us was how good all the men were with firearms. It's because we all served in the military. In Korea, military service is mandatory, so we were all pretty skilled. It was both surprising and kind of fun to see. Though I'd never actually used a handgun before. So I was a little clumsy at first, but Byung-hun gave me some tips. Thanks to him, we were able to get through the scene smoothly. For me, during the brutal bathroom fight scene you saw earlier, together with Jung-hae... While we were filming, near the end of the shoot, I actually cracked a rib during the last part of the action. It was pretty painful, but luckily it happened close to the end. So I just pushed through the pain and kept filming. One funny memory: Director Hwang came over, looking genuinely concerned. But he said, 'At least it happened on the last day.' 'If it happened earlier, it would've delayed the shoot a lot.' 'So really, it's a good thing it happened at the end.' That's when I thought, 'Ah, our director really is completely immersed in his craft.' Totally a director through and through. In the final scene, Thanos goes out like a totally wild troublemaker. He causes chaos one last time, and gets taken out in such an impactful way. I'm really grateful for how memorably I was sent off. Director Hwang was the one who guided me the most throughout the shoot. The direction I heard most often from him was 'Tone it down a bit,' or 'Go a little crazier.' He'd switch between those depending on the moment. I think we both felt that this character's awkward, over-the-top side made him more than just your typical villain. He's unpredictable, a loose cannon. We wanted to create someone truly unique and offbeat. So I had a lot of fun talking it through with Director Hwang and bringing it to life. At first, I wanted to carry over a lot of Gi-hun's energy from Season 1 into Season 2. That was the direction I was thinking of taking with my performance. But Director Hwang had a different vision. He wanted Gi-hun to take on a more central, stabilizing role throughout the whole season. And he also asked me to express emotions in a way that felt weighty and restrained. So rather than staying consistent with the Gi-hun from Season 1, he wanted him to appear quite different in Season 2. And I tried my best to shape my acting to match that intention, gradually building up this newer version of Gi-hun. But even so, I did wonder if there was a way to still show glimpses of the Gi-hun people loved in Season 2. Thankfully, through the character Jeong-dae, we were able to do that. And soon, when Season 3 is released, you'll see yet another transformation in Gi-hun. Especially following the death of Jeong-dae, his character changes again. And I think viewers will be able to clearly see that shift. So in a way, Gi-hun's emotional evolution through Seasons 1, 2, and 3 reflects his changing inner world and the kinds of choices he makes in response to those changes. You may find yourself wondering what direction he'll take next, and at times even be surprised by the decisions he makes. That kind of unexpected emotional journey is something you'll get to fully experience in Season 3. That's all I can say. Well, thank you all so much for your time and your insights. Please give it up for the cast of Squid Game. Thank you. Thank you so much.",
      "summary": "Choi Seung-hyun discusses the personal growth he experienced while playing the drug-addicted rapper Thanos. Director Hwang Dong-hyuk elaborates on Season 2's themes of democracy and voting, reflecting on real-world political divisions. Lee Byung-hun explains the Front Man's complex obsession with Gi-hun, seeing him as a reflection of his lost self. The actors share behind-the-scenes stories about stunt training and injuries, and Lee Jung-jae teases Gi-hun's further evolution in Season 3."
    }
  ]
